Question: How to use AsyncTask in Android?:
I have a button click event that starts an AsyncTask. The AsyncTask is supposed to perform a long running task and then update a TextView in the UI.
-> I have a button click event that starts an AsyncTask:
Button button = (Button) findViewById(R.id.button);
button.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    public void onClick(View view) {
        new MyAsyncTask().execute();
    }
});

-> MyAsyncTask class:
private class MyAsyncTask extends AsyncTask<Void, Void, String> {
    @Override
    protected String doInBackground(Void... params) {
        // Perform long running task here
        return "Task Completed";
    }

    @Override
    protected void onPostExecute(String result) {
        TextView textView = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.textView);
        textView.setText(result);
    }
}

-> The problem is that the TextView is not updated. What am I doing wrong?
Answer: The problem is that you are trying to update the TextView from a non-UI thread. In Android, you must not update the UI from a background thread. The AsyncTask.onPostExecute() method is run on the UI thread, so you can safely update the UI here.

Here is the corrected code:
Button button = (Button) findViewById(R.id.button);
button.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    public void onClick(View view) {
        new MyAsyncTask().execute();
    }
});

private class MyAsyncTask extends AsyncTask<Void, Void, String> {
    @Override
    protected String doInBackground(Void... params) {
        // Perform long running task here
        return "Task Completed";
    }

    @Override
    protected void onPostExecute(String result) {
        TextView textView = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.textView);
        textView.setText(result);
    }
}

